						               													<description>A cross between Rummy and Miles Borne - family fun for anyone who loves the beach and card games.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Collect Sandcastles and Seashells, but you can steal them with Pirates or Hermit Crabs!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Objective:&amp;#10;Make 2 sets of blue cards to win!   It&amp;rsquo;ll say on each Blue Card how many are in a set.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Setup:&amp;#10;Give each player a Player Card (1 Surfer).&amp;#10;Deal 6 cards to each player (as their hand, face up) and 10 cards face-up as The Ocean.   &amp;#10;The Discard pile is face up next to the deck (reuse if you finish the deck).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Gameplay:&amp;#10;Play goes clockwise.  Each turn, a player can do one of the following:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;    Place your Surfer on a card in the Ocean&amp;#10;    Draw 1 card from the Deck or under your Surfer and then put 1 card in the Ocean&amp;#10;    Play a Yellow Card from your hand&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Action Card Notes&amp;#10;&amp;#10;    Discard means to the Discard Pile&amp;#10;    Take a card means from the Ocean or another player; not from under a Surfer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The first game, the person most recently at the beach goes first.  After that, the winner goes last.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;And most importantly: please enjoy A Day at the Beach!!!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Full official rules at http://www.standardgames.com&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Purchase the game at:&amp;#10;https://www.thegamecrafter.com/games/a-day-at-the-beach&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Artist: Emma Glennon&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
